tspan.tspan: If an equal number of text objects are selected as rectangles, the style of the text
objects are copied column by column, including font weight, font family, and text
Create a number of rectangles so that they look like one row of the table you want
and style them however you like. Select them and choose Extensions -> Data
Columns will be spaced as the original rectangles. The dialog allows you to add
space in between rows. The resulting table is contained in a group, where the cell
rectangles and text objects each have their own subgroup. This makes it easy to
tab through and enter data values, or change specific cells attributes after the fact.
You can choose to add vertical and/or horizontal internal grid lines, and/or a
bounding frame around the whole table. The grid lines and bounding box are
in their own group and so can be styled altogether or independently.
You can also select one text box (click and drag w/ text tool, creates a
<flowRoot/> tag) and put comma separated values into it that will be used to
populate the table. This isn't super robust, make sure the number of data fields
equals the number of fields you specify to be in the table. Even so, no promises.
